While the Leica M6 is on long term loan to a friend, I decided to take the Leica M10 along with me to a trip to Old Sacramento. I've been shooting with the M10 for a while now - I really do believe it's the closest you're going to come to getting a manual, mechanical "film camera" exerience with a digital camera. "Close" being the operative word. It handles well and if you've familiarity with a Leica or most any rangefinder, it's going to be a familiar place for you. One thing that still causes an issue for me, personally, is the viewfinder magnifaction. At .73, and with supposedly better eye relief than the cameras that came with it, the fact that I'm a glasses-wearing left-eyed shooter makes it impossible to see all the framelines with a 35mm focal length lens. 50mm and longer works great, but 35mm is my favorite to use on a daily basis. I've always felt that 50mm is too tight for everyday use for me--even after using it almost exclusively for a year. 35mm just feels like home. The files are great, of course--lots of lattitude, very malleable, lots of room to crop. One thing I always do with RAW files is to use Adobe Lightroom's Color Grading feature to make highlights sligtly wamer, and shadows slightly cooler. I create presets for myself for efficiency's sake and then make WB and exposure adjustments from there. If anyone wants the preset, DM me and I'll send it to you
.

"Cursed: The House of Atreus" Dir. @latinxtheatreartist, starring @eryn.yoo @vicki_zaragoza_ @willparsley317 @mmcamachojr @a.siabee @dauntebruuh_ @guppy_2027 @austintrenholm @shameliar @bg_bellers @harriejx with special thanks to @labarredirects for entrusting me to document this production for @ccctheatrelive. For my photography folks: I migrated completely to the @sonyalpha system January of this year with absolutely zero regrets. Far more of a fast action interface and performance than my previous system, all shot with RAW files and edited in Lightroom. I created a preset specifically for this somewhat difficult lighting situation of white clothing on a dark background, utilizing some color grading to help balance the shadows with the highlights, but also help separate them visually and to naturalize the skin tones, as there is no system that can nail it in-camera. I'm going to post a before/after reel, too. If you want the preset, DM me! YMMV depending on your camera system.
